<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-589-614 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 589 614</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 15 1991 v8 n15 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus breaks out on 3Com's campus net: prompt response lets vendorcontain outbreak, purge infected files and minimize data loss.andO;(3Com Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gillooly, Caryn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Network vendor 3Com Corp was forced to shut down portions of its5,000-node campus network in Santa Clara, CA due to a computervirus.andP;  Portions of the network were down for an entire day whilestaff LAN administrators isolated infected workstations anddeleted infected files.andP;  Users first noticed the virus whenworkstations started locking up and unusual pictures appeared onscreens.andP;  Network administrators, upon realizing that a virus wasinfecting the network, shut down individual LANs in phases so thatthe network was never fully down.andP;  3 Com already had a plan inplace which had been rehearsed periodically and led to the promptresponse and minimal data loss.andP;  Officials are unsure as to howthe virus entered the network but emphasize that no engineering orcode-production networks were infected.andP;  Characteristics of thevirus match those associated with the Jerusalem virus which isprogrammed to replicate itself and attach to executable files.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   3Com Corp. (Communication systems).andO;Ticker:    COMS.andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesLocal Area NetworksData SecurityWorkstationsFile Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>